{"warnings":{"query":{"*":"Formatting of continuation data will be changing soon. To continue using the current formatting, use the 'rawcontinue' parameter. To begin using the new format, pass an empty string for 'continue' in the initial query."}},"query":{"pages":{"8470550":{"pageid":8470550,"ns":0,"title":"Aragorn (comics)","revisions":[{"contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Superherobox| <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics--> \n|image=[[Image:ValkyrieDefenders4.jpg|200px]]\n|caption=\n|comic_color=background:#ff8080 \n|character_name=Aragorn\n|real_name=Aragorn\n|species=\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut=''[[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]]'' #48 (Jan 1968)\n|creators=[[Roy Thomas]] and [[George Tuska]]\n|alliances= \n|partners=[[Black Knight (Dane Whitman)|Black Knight]]<br>[[Valkyrie (Marvel Comics)|Valkyrie]]\n|aliases=Hellhorse \n|powers=Flight via feathered wings<br>Enhanced intelligence<br>Experienced battle steed \n|}} \n'''Aragorn''' was a [[fictional character|fictional]] winged [[horse]] that has served as a mount for various characters in [[Marvel Comics]].\n\n==Fictional character biography==\n===First Aragorn===\nProfessor Nathan Garrett, the criminal [[Black Knight (Nathan Garrett)|Black Knight]], developed genetic engineering techniques capable of granting a horse wings. He uses it to create a mount to ride during his criminal adventures.<ref>''Avengers'' vol 1 #48</ref> After Garrett's final defeat by [[Iron Man]], this horse escapes, was further mutated, and fell into the possession of the [[Dreadknight]] who named it '''Hellhorse'''.<ref>''Tales of Suspense'' vol. 1 #73</ref>\n\n===Second Aragorn===\nAs Garrett was dying, he persuades his nephew Dane Whitman to take his scientific discoveries and use them for good. Whitman thus became a new, heroic [[Black Knight (Dane Whitman)|Black Knight]], and used his uncle's techniques to create another flying horse. This one he names Aragorn and uses as his mount.<ref>''Avengers'' #48</ref> Aragorn helped the Black Knight and the [[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]] battle the [[Masters of Evil]];<ref>''Avengers'' #55</ref> carried the Black Knight into battle against [[Le Sabre (comics)|Le Sabre]];<ref>''Marvel Super-Heroes'' Vol. 2 #17</ref> helped the Black Knight and [[Doctor Strange]] battle [[Tiboro]];<ref>''Doctor Strange'' Vol. 1 #178</ref> carried the Black Knight alongside Doctor Strange, and the Avengers as they battled [[Ymir (Marvel Comics)|Ymir]] and [[Surtur (Marvel Comics)|Surtur]];<ref>''Avengers'' #61</ref> carried the Black Knight to [[Olympus (Marvel Comics)|Olympus]] to battle [[Ares (Marvel Comics)|Ares]] and the [[Enchantress (Marvel Comics)|Enchantress]],<ref>''Avengers'' #100</ref> among numerous other adventures together.\n\nWhen the Black Knight was turned into stone by the Enchantress, Aragorn was placed in the custody of his fellow [[Defenders (comics)|Defender]], the [[Valkyrie (Marvel Comics)|Valkyrie]].<ref>''Defenders'' #4</ref> Aragorn carried the Valkyrie and [[Namorita]] into battle against the [[Omegatron]].<ref>''Defenders'' #5</ref> When Whitman left his own time to stay for a while in the 12th Century AD, he entrusted Aragorn to the care of the Valkyrie, who became his permanent companion.<ref>''Defenders'' #11</ref> He came to live at the Richmond Riding Academy.<ref>''Defenders'' #17</ref> He accompanied the Valkyrie to [[Asgard (comics)|Asgard]] and Valhalla, and helped Valkyrie, [[Harokin]], and the Defenders battle [[Ollerus (comics)|Ollerus]] and [[Casiolena]].<ref>''Defenders'' #66-68</ref> With Valkyrie, Aragorn helped form the New Defenders.<ref>''Defenders'' #126</ref>\n\nWhile Aragorn was with Valkyrie, Dane Whitman gained a new flying horse named Strider from the [[Lady of the Lake]].<ref>''Heroes for Hire'' #2</ref>\n\nAragorn is still in the company of Valkyrie.<ref>''Hulk'' #7, ''She-Hulk'' #34</ref>\n\n===Third Aragorn===\nAnother Aragon served as a steed to Augustine du Lac who is the Vatican Black Knight. He rode Aragorn at the time when he accompanied [[Klaw (Marvel Comics)|Klaw]] in his invasion of [[Wakanda (comics)|Wakanda]].<ref>''Black Panther'' Vol. 4 #3</ref>\n\nWhen [[Kraven the Hunter]]'s son [[Kraven the Hunter (Alyosha Kravinoff)|Alyosha Kravinoff]] began collecting a [[zoo]] of animal themed superbeings, Aragorn is clearly seen in one of the cages. However, after disobeying Kraven, Aragorn was killed to set an example to his other captives and then served up as food. <ref>''[[Punisher War Journal]]'' Vol. 2 #13-14</ref> The Marvel Pets Handbook confirmed that the Aragorn killed by Alyosha Kravinoff was the Vatican Black Knight's Aragorn.<ref>''[[Marvel Pets Handbook]]''</ref>\n\n==Powers and abilities==\nAragorn was a normal horse until [[Black Knight (Dane Whitman)|Dane Whitman]] used [[Black Knight (Nathan Garrett)|Nathan Garrett]]'s techniques to give him large, fully feathered wings that allow him to fly. He is an experienced battle steed on land and aloft. Aragorn's enhanced intelligence gives him an excellent rapport with both the [[Valkyrie (Marvel Comics)|Valkyrie]] and Dane Whitman, enabling him to understand and obey complex commands.\n\n==In other media==\n===Television===\n* The Vatican Black Knight's Aragorn appears in the ''[[Black Panther (TV series)|Black Panther]]'' TV series. The Vatican Black Knight rides Aragorn during Klaw's invasion of Wakanda.\n\n===Film===\n* Aragorn appears in a few scenes in the direct-to-video animated film ''[[Hulk Vs]]'' during the \"Hulk vs Thor\" segment. As in the comics, he appears as Valkyrie's steed, who leads the Asgardian warriors to protect [[Odin (comics)|Odin]] from the Hulk's rampage.\n\n===Video games===\n* Aragorn appears in ''[[Marvel: Avengers Alliance]]''. He can be summoned as part of Valkyrie's \"Flight of Valkyrie\" attack.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://marvel.wikia.com/Aragorn_%28Earth-616%29 Aragorn] at Marvel Wiki\n* [http://marvel.wikia.com/Aragorn_%28Vatican%27s_Black_Knight%29_%28Earth-616%29 Vatican Black Knight's Aragorn] at Marvel Wiki\n* [http://www.comicvine.com/aragorn/4005-6810/ Aragorn] at Comic Vine\n\n{{Thor}}\n\n[[Category:Characters created by Roy Thomas]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1968]]\n[[Category:Fictional horses]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics superheroes]]"}]}}}}